**Version**
3.1.2

**Steps to reproduce**

```javascript
// store/modules/todo.js
export default {
  namespaced: true,
  state: {
    todos: [
      { id: 1, title: 'something todo' }
    ]
  },
  getters: {
    getTodo: state => id => state.todos.filter(todo => todo.id === id)[0]
  }
}


// a component.vue
methods: {
  ...mapGetters('todo', ['getTodo']),
  someMethod: {
    console.log(this.getTodo(1))

    // this work!
    console.log(this.getTodo()(1))
  }
}

```

**What is expected?**

```this.getTodo(1)``` should return ``` {id: 1, title: 'something todo'}```

**What is actually happening?**

it return a callable function same as ```getTodo```: 
```javascript
ƒ (id) {
  return state.filter(function (s) {
    return s.id == id;
  })[0];
}
```

-----
There is no more details about how to use ```mapGetters``` with **namespaced** module in the [doc](https://vuex.vuejs.org/api/#mapgetters).
Am I miss something or it should not be used in this way?

### What problem does this feature solve?
If the getter returns an object or an array, this causes a recalculation of the properties that depend on this getter, even if the data in the object that returned the getter did not change. Can I somehow return the result of a previous getter calculation if the data has not really changed?

### What does the proposed API look like?
`someGetter(state, getters, rootState, rootGetters, oldValue) {
...
if (JSON.stringify(result) === JSON.stringify(oldValue)) return oldValue;
return result;
}`

